PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_9baseutils_111smoothing, " Smooth data along axis. \n    \n    Parameters \n    -----------\n    ar: ArrayLike 1d or 2d \n       One dimensional or two dimensional array. \n       \n    drop_outliers: bool, default=True \n       Remove the outliers in the data before smoothing along the given axis \n       \n    ma: bool, default=True, \n       Use the moving average for smoothing array value along axis. This seems \n       more realistic rather than using only the scaling method. \n       \n    absolute: bool, default=False, \n       keep positive the extrapolated scaled values. Indeed, when scaling data, \n       negative value can be appear due to the polyfit function. to absolute \n       this value, set ``absolute=True``. Note that converting to values to \n       positive must be considered as the last option when values in the \n       array must be positive.\n       \n    axis: int, default=0 \n       Axis along with the data must be smoothed. The default is the along  \n       the row. \n       \n    view: bool, default =False \n       Visualize the two dimensional raw and smoothing grid. \n       \n    xlabel: str, optional \n       Label of x \n       \n    ylabel:str, optional \n    \n       label of y  \n    fig_size: tuple , default=(7, 5)\n       Matplotlib figure size \n       \n    cmap: str, default='binary'\n       Matplotlib.colormap to manage the `view` color \n      \n    Return \n    --------\n    arr0: ArrayLike \n       Smoothed array value. \n    \n    Examples \n    ---------\n    >>> import numpy as np \n    >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils  import smoothing\n    >>> # add Guassian Noises \n    >>> np.random.seed (42)\n    >>> ar = np.random.randn (20, 7 ) * 20 + np.random.normal ( 20, 7 )\n    >>> ar [:3, :3 ]\n    array([[ 31.5265026 ,  18.82693352,  34.5459903 ],\n           [ 36.94091413,  12.20273182,  32.44342041],\n           [-12.90613711,  10.34646896,   1.33559714]])\n    >>> arc = smoothing (ar, view =True , ma =False )\n    >>> arc [:3, :3 ]\n    array(""[[32.20356863, 17.18624398, 41.22258603],\n           [33.46353806, 15.56839464, 19.20963317],\n           [23.22466498, 13.8985316 ,  5.04748584]])\n    >>> arcma = smoothing (ar, view =True )# ma=True by default\n    >>> arcma [:3, :3 ]\n    array([[23.96547827,  8.48064226, 31.81490918],\n           [26.21374675, 13.33233065, 12.29345026],\n           [22.60143346, 16.77242118,  2.07931194]])\n    >>> arcma_1 = smoothing (ar, view =True, axis =1 )\n    >>> arcma_1 [:3, :3 ]\n    array([[18.74017857, 26.91532187, 32.02914421],\n           [18.4056216 , 21.81293014, 21.98535213],\n           [-1.44359989,  3.49228057,  7.51734762]])\n    ");

 3700:     """ Smooth data along axis.
 3701: 
 3702:     Parameters
 3703:     -----------
 3704:     ar: ArrayLike 1d or 2d
 3705:        One dimensional or two dimensional array.
 3706: 
 3707:     drop_outliers: bool, default=True
 3708:        Remove the outliers in the data before smoothing along the given axis
 3709: 
 3710:     ma: bool, default=True,
 3711:        Use the moving average for smoothing array value along axis. This seems
 3712:        more realistic rather than using only the scaling method.
 3713: 
 3714:     absolute: bool, default=False,
 3715:        keep positive the extrapolated scaled values. Indeed, when scaling data,
 3716:        negative value can be appear due to the polyfit function. to absolute
 3717:        this value, set ``absolute=True``. Note that converting to values to
 3718:        positive must be considered as the last option when values in the
 3719:        array must be positive.
 3720: 
 3721:     axis: int, default=0
 3722:        Axis along with the data must be smoothed. The default is the along
 3723:        the row.
 3724: 
 3725:     view: bool, default =False
 3726:        Visualize the two dimensional raw and smoothing grid.
 3727: 
 3728:     xlabel: str, optional
 3729:        Label of x
 3730: 
 3731:     ylabel:str, optional
 3732: 
 3733:        label of y
 3734:     fig_size: tuple , default=(7, 5)
 3735:        Matplotlib figure size
 3736: 
 3737:     cmap: str, default='binary'
 3738:        Matplotlib.colormap to manage the `view` color
 3739: 
 3740:     Return
 3741:     --------
 3742:     arr0: ArrayLike
 3743:        Smoothed array value.
 3744: 
 3745:     Examples
 3746:     ---------
 3747:     >>> import numpy as np
 3748:     >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils  import smoothing
 3749:     >>> # add Guassian Noises
 3750:     >>> np.random.seed (42)

 3758:     array([[32.20356863, 17.18624398, 41.22258603],
 3759:            [33.46353806, 15.56839464, 19.20963317],
 3760:            [23.22466498, 13.8985316 ,  5.04748584]])

 3762:     >>> arcma [:3, :3 ]

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_9baseutils_115scale_y, "\n    Scaling value using a fitting curve.\n\n    Create polyfit function from specific data points `x` to correct `y` \n    values.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    y : ArrayLike\n        Array-like of y-axis. This is the array of values to be scaled.\n    x : ArrayLike, optional\n        Array-like of x-axis. If `x` is given, it should be the same length \n        as `y`, otherwise an error will occur. Default is ``None``.\n    deg : int, optional\n        Polynomial degree. If value is ``auto`` or ``None``, it will be computed \n        using the length of extrema (local and/or global) values.\n    func : _F, optional\n        Callable - The model function, ``f(x, ...)``. It must take the \n        independent variable as the first argument and the parameters to \n        fit as separate remaining arguments. `func` can be a ``linear`` \n        function i.e. for ``f(x)= ax + b`` where `a` is slope and `b` is \n        the intercept value. It is recommended to set up a custom function \n        according to the `y` value distribution for better fitting. If \n        `func` is given, `deg` is not needed.\n    return_xf : bool, optional\n        If True, returns the new x-axis and the fitting function. Default \n        is ``False``.\n    view : bool, optional\n        If True, visualizes the original and scaled data. Default is \n        ``False``.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    yc : ArrayLike\n        Array of scaled/projected sample values obtained from `f`.\n    x : ArrayLike\n        New x-axis generated from the samples (if `return_xf` is True).\n    f : _F\n        Linear or polynomial function `f` (if `return_xf` is True).\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> import numpy as np\n    >>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n    >>> np.random.seed(42)\n    >>> x0 = 10 * np.random.rand(50)\n    >>> y = 2 * x0 + np.random.randn(50) - 1\n    >>> plt.scatter(x0, y)\n    >>> yc, x, f = scale_y(y, return_xf=True, view=True)\n    >>> plt.plot(x, y, label='Origi""nal Data')\n    >>> plt.plot(x, yc, label='Scaled Data')\n    >>> plt.legend()\n    >>> plt.show()\n\n    Notes\n    -----\n    - The function checks if `x` and `y` are of the same length.\n    - If `func` is provided, `deg` is ignored.\n    - The function raises a `TypeError` if `func` is not callable.\n    - The degree of the polynomial is determined by the number of local \n      minima plus one.\n    - In case of fitting errors, a `ValueError` is raised with a suggestion \n      to check the polynomial degree.\n      \n    References \n    -----------\n    Wikipedia, Curve fitting, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve_fitting\n    Wikipedia, Polynomial interpolation, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_interpolation\n    ");

 3858:         the intercept value. It is recommended to set up a custom function
 3859:         according to the `y` value distribution for better fitting. If
 3860:         `func` is given, `deg` is not needed.
 3861:     return_xf : bool, optional
 3862:         If True, returns the new x-axis and the fitting function. Default
 3863:         is ``False``.
 3864:     view : bool, optional
 3865:         If True, visualizes the original and scaled data. Default is
 3866:         ``False``.
 3867: 
 3868:     Returns
 3869:     -------
 3870:     yc : ArrayLike
 3871:         Array of scaled/projected sample values obtained from `f`.
 3872:     x : ArrayLike
 3873:         New x-axis generated from the samples (if `return_xf` is True).
 3874:     f : _F
 3875:         Linear or polynomial function `f` (if `return_xf` is True).
 3876: 
 3877:     Examples
 3878:     --------
 3879:     >>> import numpy as np
 3880:     >>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
 3881:     >>> np.random.seed(42)
 3882:     >>> x0 = 10 * np.random.rand(50)
 3883:     >>> y = 2 * x0 + np.random.randn(50) - 1
 3884:     >>> plt.scatter(x0, y)
 3885:     >>> yc, x, f = scale_y(y, return_xf=True, view=True)
 3886:     >>> plt.plot(x, y, label='Original Data')
 3887:     >>> plt.plot(x, yc, label='Scaled Data')
 3888:     >>> plt.legend()
 3889:     >>> plt.show()
 3890: 
 3891:     Notes
 3892:     -----
 3893:     - The function checks if `x` and `y` are of the same length.
 3894:     - If `func` is provided, `deg` is ignored.
 3895:     - The function raises a `TypeError` if `func` is not callable.
 3896:     - The degree of the polynomial is determined by the number of local
 3897:       minima plus one.
 3898:     - In case of fitting errors, a `ValueError` is raised with a suggestion
 3899:       to check the polynomial degree.
 3900: 
 3901:     References
 3902:     -----------
 3903:     Wikipedia, Curve fitting, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve_fitting
 3904:     Wikipedia, Polynomial interpolation, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_interpolation
 3905:     """

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_9baseutils_119interpolate_data, "\n    Interpolates 1D or 2D data, allowing for NaN values, and visualizes \n    the result if requested.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    data : Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]\n        Input data to be interpolated. Can be a 1D or 2D numpy array, \n        pandas Series, or pandas DataFrame.\n    method : str, optional\n        Method of interpolation. Options include 'linear', 'nearest', \n        'zero', 'slinear', 'quadratic', and 'cubic'. Default is 'slinear'.\n    order : Optional[int], optional\n        The order of the spline interpolation. Only applicable for some \n        methods. Default is None.\n    fill_value : str, optional\n        Specifies the fill value for points outside the interpolation \n        domain. Default is 'extrapolate'.\n    axis : int, optional\n        Axis along which to interpolate, if data is a DataFrame. Default \n        is 0.\n    drop_outliers : bool, optional\n        If True, outliers will be removed before interpolation. Default \n        is False.\n    outlier_method : str, optional\n        Method for outlier detection if drop_outliers is True. Options \n        are 'IQR' and 'z-score'. Default is 'IQR'.\n    view : bool, optional\n        If True, visualizes the original and interpolated data in two \n        panels. Default is False.\n    **kwargs\n        Additional keyword arguments to pass to the interpolation \n        function.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]\n        Interpolated data, returned in the same type as the input data.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> import numpy as np\n    >>> import pandas as pd \n    >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils import interpolate_data\n    >>> s = pd.Series([1, np.nan, 3, 4, np.nan, 6])\n    >>> interpolate_data(s, view=True)\n    0    1.0\n    1    2.0\n    2    3.0\n    3    4.0\n    4    5.0\n    5    6.0\n    dtype: float64\n\n    >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, np.nan, 3], [4, 5, np.nan], [np.nan, 8, 9]])\n    "">>> interpolate_data(df, view=True)\n         0    1    2\n    0  1.0  6.5  3.0\n    1  4.0  5.0  6.0\n    2  4.0  8.0  9.0\n\n    Notes\n    -----\n    - The 'slinear' method is not available for 2D interpolation. It \n      defaults to 'linear' for 2D data.\n    - The 'extrapolate' fill_value is not available for 2D interpolation \n      and defaults to 0.\n    - If drop_outliers is True, the specified outlier detection method \n      will be applied before interpolation.\n    ");

 3977:     Interpolates 1D or 2D data, allowing for NaN values, and visualizes

 3979: 
 3980:     Parameters
 3981:     ----------
 3982:     data : Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]
 3983:         Input data to be interpolated. Can be a 1D or 2D numpy array,
 3984:         pandas Series, or pandas DataFrame.
 3985:     method : str, optional
 3986:         Method of interpolation. Options include 'linear', 'nearest',
 3987:         'zero', 'slinear', 'quadratic', and 'cubic'. Default is 'slinear'.
 3988:     order : Optional[int], optional
 3989:         The order of the spline interpolation. Only applicable for some
 3990:         methods. Default is None.
 3991:     fill_value : str, optional
 3992:         Specifies the fill value for points outside the interpolation
 3993:         domain. Default is 'extrapolate'.
 3994:     axis : int, optional
 3995:         Axis along which to interpolate, if data is a DataFrame. Default
 3996:         is 0.
 3997:     drop_outliers : bool, optional
 3998:         If True, outliers will be removed before interpolation. Default
 3999:         is False.
 4000:     outlier_method : str, optional
 4001:         Method for outlier detection if drop_outliers is True. Options
 4002:         are 'IQR' and 'z-score'. Default is 'IQR'.
 4003:     view : bool, optional
 4004:         If True, visualizes the original and interpolated data in two
 4005:         panels. Default is False.
 4006:     **kwargs
 4007:         Additional keyword arguments to pass to the interpolation
 4008:         function.
 4009: 
 4010:     Returns
 4011:     -------
 4012:     Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]
 4013:         Interpolated data, returned in the same type as the input data.
 4014: 
 4015:     Examples
 4016:     --------
 4017:     >>> import numpy as np
 4018:     >>> import pandas as pd
 4019:     >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils import interpolate_data

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_9baseutils_121denormalizer, "\n    Denormalizes data from a normalized scale back to its original scale.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    data : Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]\n        The data to be denormalized, can be a NumPy array, \n        pandas Series, or pandas DataFrame.\n    min_value : float\n        The minimum value of the original scale before normalization.\n    max_value : float\n        The maximum value of the original scale before normalization.\n    method : str, optional\n        The normalization method used. Supported methods are:\n        - '01' : Min-Max normalization to range [0, 1].\n        - 'zscore' : Standard score normalization (zero mean, unit variance).\n        - 'sum' : Normalization by sum of elements.\n        Default is '01'.\n    std_dev_factor : float, optional\n        The factor determining the range for standard deviation. \n        This is used only for 'zscore' method. Default is 3.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]\n        The denormalized data, converted back to its original scale.\n\n    Raises\n    ------\n    ValueError\n        If an unsupported normalization method is provided.\n\n    Notes\n    -----\n    The denormalization process depends on the normalization method:\n    \n    - For Min-Max normalization ('01'):\n     .. math:: \n         \n         `denormalized\\_data = data \\cdot (max\\_value - min\\_value) + min\\_value`\n    \n    - For z-score normalization ('zscore'):\n      Assuming the original data follows a normal distribution:\n          \n      .. math:: \n          `denormalized\\_data = data \\cdot std\\_dev + mean`\n      where \n      \n      .. math::\n          `mean = \014rac{min\\_value + max\\_value}{2}`\n      and \n      \n      .. math::\n          `std\\_dev = \014rac{max\\_value - min\\_value}{2 \\cdot std\\_dev\\_factor}`\n    \n    - For sum normalization ('sum'):\n        \n      .. math::\n          \n          `denormalized\\_data = data \\cdot ""\014rac{max\\_value - min\\_value}{\\sum(data)} + min\\_value`\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> import numpy as np\n    >>> import pandas as pd\n    >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils import denormalizer \n    \n    >>> normalized_data = np.array([0, 0.5, 1])\n    >>> min_value = 10\n    >>> max_value = 20\n    >>> denormalized_data = denormalizer(normalized_data, min_value, max_value)\n    >>> print(denormalized_data)\n    [10. 15. 20.]\n\n    >>> normalized_series = pd.Series([0, 0.5, 1])\n    >>> denormalized_series = denormalizer(normalized_series, min_value, max_value)\n    >>> print(denormalized_series)\n    0    10.0\n    1    15.0\n    2    20.0\n    dtype: float64\n\n    >>> normalized_df = pd.DataFrame([[0, 0.5], [1, 0.2]])\n    >>> denormalized_df = denormalizer(normalized_df, min_value, max_value)\n    >>> print(denormalized_df)\n         0     1\n    0  10.0  15.0\n    1  20.0  12.0\n    ");

 4121:     ) -> Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]:
 4122:     """
 4123:     Denormalizes data from a normalized scale back to its original scale.
 4124: 
 4125:     Parameters
 4126:     ----------
 4127:     data : Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]
 4128:         The data to be denormalized, can be a NumPy array,
 4129:         pandas Series, or pandas DataFrame.
 4130:     min_value : float
 4131:         The minimum value of the original scale before normalization.
 4132:     max_value : float
 4133:         The maximum value of the original scale before normalization.
 4134:     method : str, optional
 4135:         The normalization method used. Supported methods are:
 4136:         - '01' : Min-Max normalization to range [0, 1].
 4137:         - 'zscore' : Standard score normalization (zero mean, unit variance).
 4138:         - 'sum' : Normalization by sum of elements.
 4139:         Default is '01'.
 4140:     std_dev_factor : float, optional
 4141:         The factor determining the range for standard deviation.
 4142:         This is used only for 'zscore' method. Default is 3.
 4143: 
 4144:     Returns
 4145:     -------
 4146:     Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame]
 4147:         The denormalized data, converted back to its original scale.
 4148: 
 4149:     Raises
 4150:     ------
 4151:     ValueError
 4152:         If an unsupported normalization method is provided.
 4153: 
 4154:     Notes
 4155:     -----
 4156:     The denormalization process depends on the normalization method:
 4157: 
 4158:     - For Min-Max normalization ('01'):
 4159:      .. math::
 4160: 
 4161:          `denormalized\_data = data \cdot (max\_value - min\_value) + min\_value`
 4162: 
 4163:     - For z-score normalization ('zscore'):
 4164:       Assuming the original data follows a normal distribution:
 4165: 
 4166:       .. math::
 4167:           `denormalized\_data = data \cdot std\_dev + mean`
 4168:       where
 4169: 
 4170:       .. math::
 4171:           `mean = \frac{min\_value + max\_value}{2}`
 4172:       and
 4173: 
 4174:       .. math::
 4175:           `std\_dev = \frac{max\_value - min\_value}{2 \cdot std\_dev\_factor}`
 4176: 
 4177:     - For sum normalization ('sum'):
 4178: 
 4179:       .. math::
 4180: 
 4181:           `denormalized\_data = data \cdot \frac{max\_value - min\_value}{\sum(data)} + min\_value`
 4182: 
 4183:     Examples
 4184:     --------
 4185:     >>> import numpy as np
 4186:     >>> import pandas as pd
 4187:     >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils import denormalizer
 4188: 
 4189:     >>> normalized_data = np.array([0, 0.5, 1])
 4190:     >>> min_value = 10
 4191:     >>> max_value = 20
 4192:     >>> denormalized_data = denormalizer(normalized_data, min_value, max_value)
 4193:     >>> print(denormalized_data)
 4194:     [10. 15. 20.]
 4195: 
 4196:     >>> normalized_series = pd.Series([0, 0.5, 1])
 4197:     >>> denormalized_series = denormalizer(normalized_series, min_value, max_value)
 4198:     >>> print(denormalized_series)
 4199:     0    10.0
 4200:     1    15.0
 4201:     2    20.0
 4202:     dtype: float64
 4203: 
 4204:     >>> normalized_df = pd.DataFrame([[0, 0.5], [1, 0.2]])
 4205:     >>> denormalized_df = denormalizer(normalized_df, min_value, max_value)
 4206:     >>> print(denormalized_df)
 4207:          0     1
 4208:     0  10.0  15.0
 4209:     1  20.0  12.0

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_9baseutils_127pandas_manager, "\n    Manages pandas objects by getting or setting data, with error handling.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    data : Any\n        The input data which can be a numpy array, pandas Series, or DataFrame.\n    todo : str, optional\n        Specifies the action to perform: 'get' or 'set'. Default is 'get'.\n    name_or_columns : Any, optional\n        Name for Series or columns for DataFrame when setting data.\n    action : str, optional\n        Specifies the sub-action for 'get': 'as_array' or 'check_only' or 'keep_frame'. \n        - `as_array` converts data to Numpy array \n        - `check_only` checks only whether the data is passed as pandas Series or \n          DataFrame\n        - `keep_frame` keeps the dataframe but returns additionals frame attributes \n          like columns/name  and index. \n        Default is 'as_array'.\n    error : str, optional\n        Error handling strategy: 'passthrough', 'raise', or 'warn'. \n        Default is 'passthrough'.\n    index : bool, optional\n        Whether to include the index when getting or setting data. Default is None.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame, Tuple[np.ndarray, Any], bool]\n        Depending on the action, returns different types of results:\n        - If `todo` is 'get' and `action` is 'check_only': returns a boolean \n          indicating if the data is a pandas object.\n        - If `todo` is 'get' and `action` is 'as_array': returns the data as \n          a NumPy array along with the original pandas attributes.\n        - If `todo` is 'set': returns the data as a pandas Series or DataFrame.\n\n    Raises\n    ------\n    ValueError\n        If the 'todo' parameter is not 'get' or 'set'.\n        If 'name_or_columns' is None when setting data and action is not 'default'.\n    TypeError\n        If the data is not a pandas Series or DataFrame when expected.\n\n \n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> import numpy as np\n    >>> import pandas as pd\n    >"">> from gofast.tools.baseutils import pandas_manager\n\n    Get action with pandas DataFrame:\n    >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2], [3, 4]], columns=['A', 'B'])\n    >>> array, columns, index = pandas_manager(df, todo='get', action='as_array')\n    >>> print(array)\n    [[1 2]\n     [3 4]]\n    >>> print(columns)\n    Index(['A', 'B'], dtype='object')\n\n    Set action with 1D numpy array:\n    >>> arr = np.array([1, 2, 3])\n    >>> series = pandas_manager(arr, todo='set', name_or_columns='Value')\n    >>> print(series)\n    0    1\n    1    2\n    2    3\n    Name: Value, dtype: int64\n\n    Set action with 2D numpy array:\n    >>> arr_2d = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]])\n    >>> df_2d = pandas_manager(arr_2d, todo='set', name_or_columns=['A', 'B'])\n    >>> print(df_2d)\n       A  B\n    0  1  2\n    1  3  4\n    ");

 4294:     Manages pandas objects by getting or setting data, with error handling.

 4304:     action : str, optional

 4306:         - `as_array` converts data to Numpy array
 4307:         - `check_only` checks only whether the data is passed as pandas Series or
 4308:           DataFrame
 4309:         - `keep_frame` keeps the dataframe but returns additionals frame attributes
 4310:           like columns/name  and index.
 4311:         Default is 'as_array'.

 4313:         Error handling strategy: 'passthrough', 'raise', or 'warn'.
 4314:         Default is 'passthrough'.
 4315:     index : bool, optional
 4316:         Whether to include the index when getting or setting data. Default is None.
 4317: 
 4318:     Returns
 4319:     -------
 4320:     Union[np.ndarray, pd.Series, pd.DataFrame, Tuple[np.ndarray, Any], bool]
 4321:         Depending on the action, returns different types of results:
 4322:         - If `todo` is 'get' and `action` is 'check_only': returns a boolean
 4323:           indicating if the data is a pandas object.
 4324:         - If `todo` is 'get' and `action` is 'as_array': returns the data as
 4325:           a NumPy array along with the original pandas attributes.
 4326:         - If `todo` is 'set': returns the data as a pandas Series or DataFrame.

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_9baseutils_129make_df, "\n    Prepare a DataFrame from input data `X` and `y` with appropriate naming\n    conventions and length checks.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    X : array-like or DataFrame\n        Input features. If not a DataFrame, `X` will be converted into one with \n        column names generated using the `prefix` parameter.\n\n    y : array-like or Series, optional\n        Target values. If provided, `y` will be converted into a DataFrame. \n        If `y` is a 1D array and `target_names` is not given, 'target' will be \n        used as the default name. For a 2D array, `target_names` will be used \n        to name the columns.\n\n    prefix : str, optional\n        Prefix for feature column names if `X` is not a DataFrame. Default is 'feature_'.\n\n    target_names : list of str, optional\n        Names for target columns if `y` is 2D. If `target_names` is not provided, \n        columns will be named using 'target_' prefix.\n\n    coerce : bool, optional\n        Whether to coerce the lengths of `X` and `y` to match if they are inconsistent.\n        Default is False. If True and `len(X) < len(y)`, `X` will be repeated to \n        match `y`'s length. If `len(y) < len(X)`, `y` will be forward-filled to \n        match `X`'s length.\n\n    error : str, optional\n        Error handling strategy. Options are:\n        - 'raise': Raises an error if lengths of `X` and `y` are inconsistent \n          and `coerce` is False.\n        - 'warn': Issues a warning instead of raising an error.\n        - 'ignore': Ignores the inconsistency and proceeds. Default is 'raise'.\n\n    fill_value : scalar, optional\n        Value to use for filling missing values if `coerce` is True and \n        `len(y) < len(X)`. Default is `np.nan`.\n\n    truncate_X : bool, optional\n        If True and `len(y) < len(X)`, truncate `X` to match the length of `y`.\n        Default is False.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    DataFrame\n        Combined DataFrame with features and target(s).\n\n    ""Notes\n    -----\n    This function is useful for preparing data for machine learning tasks, \n    ensuring consistency between features and targets. The function handles \n    common issues such as inconsistent lengths and missing values, providing \n    options to coerce or truncate data as needed.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils import make_df\n    >>> X = np.random.rand(90, 5)\n    >>> y = np.random.rand(100)\n    >>> df = make_data(X, y, coerce=True, error='ignore')\n    >>> print(df.head())\n\n    See Also\n    --------\n    pd.DataFrame : Pandas DataFrame constructor.\n    np.asarray : Convert input to an array.\n\n    References\n    ----------\n    .. [1] Pandas Documentation: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.html\n    ..  4386:     truncate_X=False
 4387: ):
 4388:     """
 4389:     Prepare a DataFrame from input data `X` and `y` with appropriate naming
 4390:     conventions and length checks.
 4391: 
 4392:     Parameters
 4393:     ----------
 4394:     X : array-like or DataFrame
 4395:         Input features. If not a DataFrame, `X` will be converted into one with
 4396:         column names generated using the `prefix` parameter.
 4397: 
 4398:     y : array-like or Series, optional
 4399:         Target values. If provided, `y` will be converted into a DataFrame.
 4400:         If `y` is a 1D array and `target_names` is not given, 'target' will be
 4401:         used as the default name. For a 2D array, `target_names` will be used
 4402:         to name the columns.
 4403: 
 4404:     prefix : str, optional
 4405:         Prefix for feature column names if `X` is not a DataFrame. Default is 'feature_'.
 4406: 
 4407:     target_names : list of str, optional
 4408:         Names for target columns if `y` is 2D. If `target_names` is not provided,
 4409:         columns will be named using 'target_' prefix.
 4410: 
 4411:     coerce : bool, optional
 4412:         Whether to coerce the lengths of `X` and `y` to match if they are inconsistent.
 4413:         Default is False. If True and `len(X) < len(y)`, `X` will be repeated to
 4414:         match `y`'s length. If `len(y) < len(X)`, `y` will be forward-filled to
 4415:         match `X`'s length.
 4416: 
 4417:     error : str, optional
 4418:         Error handling strategy. Options are:
 4419:         - 'raise': Raises an error if lengths of `X` and `y` are inconsistent
 4420:           and `coerce` is False.
 4421:         - 'warn': Issues a warning instead of raising an error.
 4422:         - 'ignore': Ignores the inconsistency and proceeds. Default is 'raise'.
 4423: 
 4424:     fill_value : scalar, optional
 4425:         Value to use for filling missing values if `coerce` is True and
 4426:         `len(y) < len(X)`. Default is `np.nan`.
 4427: 
 4428:     truncate_X : bool, optional
 4429:         If True and `len(y) < len(X)`, truncate `X` to match the length of `y`.
 4430:         Default is False.
 4431: 
 4432:     Returns
 4433:     -------
 4434:     DataFrame
 4435:         Combined DataFrame with features and target(s).
 4436: 
 4437:     Notes
 4438:     -----
 4439:     This function is useful for preparing data for machine learning tasks,
 4440:     ensuring consistency between features and targets. The function handles
 4441:     common issues such as inconsistent lengths and missing values, providing
 4442:     options to coerce or truncate data as needed.
 4443: 
 4444:     Examples
 4445:     --------
 4446:     >>> from gofast.tools.baseutils import make_df
 4447:     >>> X = np.random.rand(90, 5)
 4448:     >>> y = np.random.rand(100)
 4449:     >>> df = make_data(X, y, coerce=True, error='ignore')
 4450:     >>> print(df.head())
 4451: 
 4452:     See Also
 4453:     --------
 4454:     pd.DataFrame : Pandas DataFrame constructor.
 4455:     np.asarray : Convert input to an array.
 4456: 
 4457:     References
 4458:     ----------
 4459:     .. [1] Pandas Documentation: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.html
 4460:     .. [2] NumPy Documentation: https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.asarray.html
 4461:     """
